<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1902-12-19T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1902-12-19T00:00:00-05:00" n="437" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d437">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Hay</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">White</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1902-12-19"><hi rend="italic">December 19,
                                    1902</hi></date>.</dateline></opener>
                        <p>(Mr. Hay acknowledges the receipt of Mr. White’s telegram mentioning the
                            President’s name as possible arbitrator, and states that <pb facs="0541" n="457" xml:id="pg_457"/> while the President would not decline any
                            service which was desired by the powers interested for the settlement of
                            pending claims he would like Mr. White to intimate, discreetly and
                            unofficially, to the British minister for foreign affairs that he would
                            regard it as altogether desirable that the matter should be referred to
                            The Hague.)</p>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>